    "source_sections": {
      "references": "",
      "remarks": "Erd\\H{o}s and Graham write that 'a proof that this cannot happen infinitely often for $\\binom{n}{2}$ seems hopeless; probably this can never happen for $\\binom{n}{k}$ if $3\\leq k\\leq n-3$.'\n\nWeisenberg has provided four easy examples that show Erd\\H{o}s and Graham were too optimistic here:\\[\\binom{7}{3}=5\\cdot 7,\\]\\[\\binom{10}{4}= 2\\cdot 3\\cdot 5\\cdot 7,\\]\\[\\binom{14}{4} = 7\\cdot 11\\cdot 13,\\]and\\[\\binom{15}{6}=5\\cdot 7\\cdot 11\\cdot 13.\\]The known values of $n$ for which $\\binom{n}{2}$ is the product of consecutive primes are $4,6,15,21,715$ (see A280992)."
    },
    "source_state": "open",
    "tags": [
      "number theory",
      "binomial coefficients"
    ]
  },
